##If the epidemic spreads globally, it could cost the global economy $1.1 trillion

The Oxford Institute estimates that the global economy could lose $1.1 trillion by 2020 if the worst case scenario turns into a global pandemic. With so much uncertainty, scenario planning is the best way for investors to cope with the potential -- especially in a market that is generally optimistic

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
By Puddy

Editor | Xiaotian Zhang

Most economists and strategists believe that the COVID-19 will be contained in the coming weeks and that the Chinese authorities will introduce a plan to cushion the economic blow. But Oxford Economics, the Oxford Economics Institute, estimates that the global economy could lose $1.1 trillion in 2020 if the worst case scenario turns into a global pandemic.

The number of new infections confirmed this week has been falling, but medical experts warn it is too early to say the danger of the outbreak has passed. As of press time, there have been nearly 75,300 confirmed cases and more than 2,000 deaths.

With so much uncertainty, scenario planning is the best way for investors to cope with the potential -- especially in a market that is generally optimistic. The S & P 500 is up nearly 5 per cent so far this year, while the Ishares Msci China ETF MCHI, which tracks Chinese companies, is up 1.6 per cent. Investors have taken some comfort from the prospect of more government stimulus to help battered companies.

In a note to clients, Oxford's chief economist, Adam Sleight Slater, wrote that if the epidemic spread globally, economic growth in the first half of the year could fall to close to zero, the US and eurozone could enter a "technical recession" . That could shave 1.3 percentage points off the 2.3 per cent baseline estimate for global growth in 2020, but could lead to a rapid recovery, with global GDP still growing at the 2.9 per cent 2021.

If the outbreak were limited to Asia, global GDP would fall by $400bn, or 0.5 percentage points, from the baseline forecast in 2020, according to the agency's projections. Growth in the asia-pacific region is set to fall from 4 per cent at the end of 2019 to 1.5 per cent in the first half of 2020, the lowest level since the global financial crisis.

These scenarios are based on past experiences with epidemics such as SARS and "swine flu" , and assume that economic pain will come from multiple sources: reduced discretionary spending when people are sick; continued travel restrictions; and People Avoiding Travel; Many people are unable to work, which hampers production; spending on travel and tourism has fallen sharply. It also assumes that investment levels will fall due to uncertainty, falling demand, supply chain disruptions and financial contagion, while stock prices fall and money market spreads rise.

But investors generally expect a "v-shaped" recovery, in which the initial shock is followed by a rapid and dramatic recovery after the epidemic is contained. Partly because of the argument that the Chinese government is introducing stimulus measures to cushion the blow -- from providing financial aid to linking factories to technology companies, to find the weak links in their supply chain.

But in a separate note to clients, Julian the Apostate Evans-Pritchard of E. E. Evans-Pritchard wrote that the employment situation could hamper the economy's ability to rebound quickly. While the vast majority of listed companies in China have enough money to sustain debt-related and compensation expenses for at least two to three months, 13 percent of companies have started laying off workers, according to a survey by Zhaopin.com. At the same time, unless economic activity rebounds "quickly" , unemployment will only get worse.

E. E. Evans-pritchard's Evans-Pritchard writes that urban workers who are self-employed or run small family businesses in China will see their incomes fall sharply in the current quarter, while those who leave their jobs in search of new ones will not find new ones.

Among listed companies, the most vulnerable are property developers. But with the exception of the worst-performing companies, most should be able to survive at least three months. More vulnerable are small and medium-sized enterprises, which account for about half of urban employment and may not comply with Beijing's directives not to cut jobs.

The E. E. Evans-pritchard, citing a survey of 1,000 such companies by two Chinese universities, found that a third would run out of money within a month unless conditions improved, the proportion of companies that run out of money in two months rose to two-thirds.

The upshot: Much is still unknown, and the recovery may not be as swift or smooth as some hope.
